{"questionId":"27792","questionHtml":"<p>Hence, by using the above integral, show that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>l</mi></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><munderover><mo>∫</mo><mn>0</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></munderover><mi>m</mi><mi>x</mi><msqrt><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mi>m</mi><msqrt><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt><msubsup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mn>0</mn><mi>h</mi></msubsup></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi>c</mi></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mi>m</mi><msqrt><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt><msubsup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mn>0</mn><mi>h</mi></msubsup></math>.&nbsp;<br>At least one of the above two lines needs to be seen.</p>\n<p><br><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><msup><mi>h</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>m</mi><msqrt><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mi>h</mi><mi>m</mi><mo>×</mo><msqrt><mfenced><mrow><msup><mi>h</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>h</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></msqrt></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>l</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Award as above if&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>l</mi><mi>h</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></math>&nbsp;is used, for example.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27792","referenceCode":"22N.3.AHL.TZ0.2b.iii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence, by using the above integral, show that A=πrl.","paper":"3","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"b.iii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.5—Integration introduction, areas between curve and x axis","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.11—Definite integrals, areas under curve onto x-axis and areas between curves"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}